title: XC394310 Black-capped Chickadee (Poecile atricapillus)
secondary_labels: ['Branta canadensis_Canada Goose']
description:
I recorded a flock of at least 6 chickadees feeding from a handheld container of peanuts and black oil sunflower seeds. The recording includes 'tseet' contact calls, 'dee-dee' calls and many gargle calls. In one case I saw one of the chickadees make a submissive posture after another chickadee made a gargle call.  The weather conditions were sunny and the temperature was around -1C with a slight breeze.

The recording also includes wing noises, the sound of a seed shell being cracked open, and the rattling of seeds in the container.

The recording was made using a Sennheiser ME-66 and a Tascam DR-05.
background: Canada Goose (Branta canadensis)
author: Dan Minor

title: XC469745 Black-capped Chickadee (Poecile atricapillus)
secondary_labels: ['Certhia americana_Brown Creeper', "Calypte anna_Anna's Hummingbird", 'Spinus pinus_Pine Siskin', 'Empidonax difficilis_Pacific-slope Flycatcher', 'Pipilo maculatus_Spotted Towhee', 'Turdus migratorius_American Robin']
description: Normalized to -3dB. 68°F, 5% cloud cover, light intermittent breeze from west. Residential setting on the edge of a greenbelt with Douglas fir and Bigleaf Maple dominant. From 0:00 to 0:42 a single bird perched 10' high in a small birch tree giving tseet calls while preening (feather ruffling audible). From the same location it then gave a series of chick-a-dee type calls beginning around 0:34.5. At 1:11 a second bird flew in and both quickly moved to a medium sized bush 25' away, at which point vocalizations changed to gargle call types (could not tell which bird), then a mix of both chick-a-dee and gargles. Two more birds landed 50' to the north and gave chick-a-dee calls. There were 4 birds total, however neither group of 2 came within 50' of each other.
background: Brown Creeper (Certhia americana); Anna's Hummingbird (Calypte anna); Pine Siskin (Spinus pinus); Pacific-slope Flycatcher (Empidonax difficilis); Spotted Towhee (Pipilo maculatus); American Robin (Turdus migratorius)
author: bowtyler

title: XC288988 Blue Jay (Cyanocitta cristata)
description:
A pair of Blue Jays foraging in isolated woody vegetation along the margins of the dry lake bed. Abnormally warm for this date, 77 F. Breezy 5-10mph SW. Distance from microphone ~30 m. 

# Habitat #
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

# Editing #
no edits other than excerpting from the raw .wav file

# Equipment #
Fostex FR-2 digital field recorder with Telinga Pro 22" parabolic reflector
author: J.R. Rigby

title: XC296398 Blue Jay (Cyanocitta cristata)

author: Nick Komar

title: XC307817 Blue Jay (Cyanocitta cristata)
secondary_labels: ['Cardinalis cardinalis_Northern Cardinal', 'Baeolophus bicolor_Tufted Titmouse', 'Bombycilla cedrorum_Cedar Waxwing']
description:
Natural sounds. Initially perched in privet in forest understory. Seemed to be harassing a Red-headed Woodpecker, following it from tree to tree and watching the woodpecker while calling. Multiple sounds including typical call, rattle/growl, and repeated mimicry of Red-shouldered Hawk. All RSHA calls in this cut are from the Blue Jay.

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

#Editing#
No edits.

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.
background: Northern Cardinal (Cardinalis cardinalis); Tufted Titmouse (Baeolophus bicolor); Cedar Waxwing (Bombycilla cedrorum)
author: J.R. Rigby

title: XC315101 Blue Jay (Cyanocitta cristata)
secondary_labels: ['Buteo platypterus_Broad-winged Hawk', 'Turdus migratorius_American Robin', 'Cardinalis cardinalis_Northern Cardinal']
description:
Natural sound. Two Blue Jays and an American Robin mobbing a Broad-winged Hawk. All three birds perched on bare limbs in the crown of a tree ~7m above the ground. Note harsh Blue Jay calls at 1:23 and 1:40 as the Blue Jay charged the hawk. Besides the occasional sallies by the Blue Jays, there was no other action or violence besides the calls. 

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 800Hz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.
background: Broad-winged Hawk (Buteo platypterus); American Robin (Turdus migratorius); Northern Cardinal (Cardinalis cardinalis)
author: J.R. Rigby

description: starts with a fight between two adult male Bullock's Orioles in the short mesquites that is the typical dawn song area, the fight continuing to 0:19 when the actual sounds during combat go on for two seconds ; an adult male Hooded also present and calling but quickly out of it if actually involved at all; the Bullock's moved off and sorted things out, and one returned and did more of the early-season dawn rattling, but there was also typical dawn song at 1:18 with a variety of interesting notes; then audible wing beats and faint ree-ree-ree suggesting another fight; too dark to see what was going on;

description:
Bullock's Oriole adult male low in short mesquites before sunrise, only a few rattles, but often audible wingbeats that I believe are deliberate, and odd, slightly ringing ree-ree-ree sounds that are the excited flight calls of the oriole, finally as it flew out past me
ree-ree-ree ringing sounds:  0:04.5, 0:25 to 0:40, 0:49, 0:56, 1:27, 1:48, 2:04, 2:38, and 3:01 (closest); these seem to continue as the bird is rattling, or is it another bird?  I have heard them a couple of other times, always linked circumstantially to Bullock's Oriole
wingbeats:  0:12, 1:31, 1:40, 3:14  as it moved around
background: House Finch (Haemorhous mexicanus); Brown-crested Flycatcher (Myiarchus tyrannulus); Hooded Oriole (Icterus cucullatus); Gambel's Quail (Callipepla gambelii)
author: Richard E. Webster

description: From the start of the dawn song except one rattle, and it is just rattles for 2:40; divided recording, this being the first part; near the end, at about 19:10 minutes [so in second part], there was a vigorous chase by this adult male (the one I have recorded often) of a bird that was not an adult male that went off into the distance, bringing song to an end for a while, plus the House Finches are taking over the acoustic environment; the singing bird made at least 11 major changes of clumps, plus additional within-clump moves, the bird singing the entire time from short mesquites (under 2m) outside of the riparian;

title: XC286644 Bullock's Oriole (Icterus bullockii)
description:
Recording extracted from a video clip. I found an oriole's nest, placed a camera there and let it record. This is the begging call of juvenile nestlings when their mother arrived with food. Original video can be viewed here: <https://vimeo.com/143237700>

Frequencies bellow cca 1.8 kHz were filtered (nothing, just wind and camera noise there) and then it was a little denoised.

title: XC420540 Bullock's Oriole (Icterus bullockii)
location: Willapa Trail, Chehalis, Lewis County, Washington
description: High pass filter, slight noise reduction. Family of Bullock's Orioles, few-day-old nestlings, calling from their nest in a cottonwood tree ~12 meters away from me. Male Oriole chatters and calls briefly during recording, as well, but my primary subject here was the nestlings, I will separate out more sounds from the adult birds another time. At least one parent feeds the nestlings during this cut. Weather: 65 degrees F, overcast, occasional sprinkle of rain.  Cottonwood in area along a slow river with many more cottonwoods, and many more Oriole families. Mixed deciduous trees and fields around area.
author: Rachel Hudson

title: XC288985 Chipping Sparrow (Spizella passerina)
description:
Perched on chain link fence. 

# Habitat #
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

# Editing #
Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, cutoff 2 khz, order 3

# Equipment #
Fostex FR-2 digital field recorder with Telinga Pro 22" parabolic reflector
author: J.R. Rigby

title: XC288993 Chipping Sparrow (Spizella passerina)
description:
Perched on the culm of Andropogon virginicus at the lake edge. With a mixed-species flock of ~25 individuals (SOSP, SWSP, CHSP, DEJU). Distance from microphone ~5 m. 60 F, calm. 

# Habitat #
Cypress Point, Sardis Lower Lake. Open hardwood grove along lakeshore.

# Editing #
Adobe Audition. FFT filter: Hamming window, 2048 pts, 5kHz-14kHz. 

# Equipment #
Fostex FR-2 digital field recorder with Telinga Pro 22" parabolic reflector
author: J.R. Rigby

*whit* calls from a bird foraging in and around a 5m juniper tree surrounded by tallgrass prairie.  Relatively weak eye-ring and wing bars, whitish throat, more yellow on belly than I expected.

Two segments, with a short gap between.

Overcast, relatively windy, and unseasonably cool.  Some light drizzle early in the morning.  Recorded with homemade parabolic reflector and Olympus LS-10S.

title: XC152448 Willow Flycatcher (Empidonax traillii)
secondary_labels: ['Dumetella carolinensis_Gray Catbird', 'Melanerpes carolinus_Red-bellied Woodpecker', 'Geothlypis trichas_Common Yellowthroat']
description: This is a recording of multiple "whit" calls of a Willow Flycatcher. The recording was made using the "voice memo" app on an iPhone 4S. The recording was slightly amplified using Audacity but is otherwise unedited. This bird has been present for nearly two months at this location, which is quite unusual, especially since this species is rarely recorded in Florida. The habitat is dense tropical shrubby hammock along a canal and road edge adjacent to a large open field. The area is just outside of the main entrance to Everglades National Park. The bird spent most of its time calling from deep within cover 5-10 feet off the ground. It briefly flew across the road and perched in the open and called a few more times. Poor photos were obtained in the early morning light.
background: Grey Catbird (Dumetella carolinensis); Red-bellied Woodpecker (Melanerpes carolinus); Common Yellowthroat (Geothlypis trichas)
author: Graham Williams

title: XC178977 Willow Flycatcher (Empidonax traillii)
secondary_labels: ['Turdus migratorius_American Robin']
description: This species has nested in a small scrubby patch of willow for many years.  It is - to the best of my knowledge - the only regular breeding location of the species in the state of Georgia.  There were actually two birds singing.  The location is very near a main artery of traffic through the town of Blairsville, and my vantage point is the only approach. Consequently there was a lot of morning noise and the recording is highly modified to accentuate the flycatcher, including noise reduction and high-pass filtering as well as discarding some sounds within the recording which would alter any perceived cadence of intervals between songs.
background: American Robin (Turdus migratorius)
author: Russ Wigh

description: Calls in response to playback from two individuals (on opposite sides of a channel) on young river island with grass, Gynerium, Cecropias, and small Tessaria. description: Fol xc277301. "whip" call at 0:1 is possibly Y-b Chat but sounds nearly identical to some variable "wit"-type calls of willow Fly males. Again, brief playback had been discontinued some time earlier- but bird may still have been responding to that from earlier- along with scattered imitated calls by me used thereafter. Although single "fitz-bew" songs are often given, I've suspected for years whether a "complete" song, usually heard given by rare local breeders here in nw La (and elsewhere?), is not actually three-parted- consisting of an initial "fitzbew.......creet....reet-beeyr" or mixed variations thereof of these three distinct calls.
background: Dickcissel (Spiza americana); Yellow-breasted Chat (Icteria virens); Common Yellowthroat (Geothlypis trichas); Northern Cardinal (Cardinalis cardinalis); Eastern Towhee (Pipilo erythrophthalmus)

title: XC370051 Willow Flycatcher (Empidonax traillii)
location: California (near  Santa Ysabel), San Diego County, California
description: Recorded using a Sony Walkman Digital Audio Tape Recorder (Sony TCD-D8) on Sony Digital Audio Tape (DAT) through a Sennheiser MKE 600 microphone. This is an unedited recording of a banded adult male on its (breeding) territory within my long-term Southwestern Willow Flycatcher study area. Call was given from the top of a large Western Sycamore (Platanus racemosa) near the center of the territory.
author: Bill Haas

title: XC81301 Willow Flycatcher (Empidonax traillii)
location: Grey Cloud Dunes SNA, Washington, Minnesota
description:
Matches the '2H' sonogram illustrated in the [BNA account for Willow Flycatcher](http://bna.birds.cornell.edu/bna/species/533/articles/sounds) (retrieved June 5, 2013), which is described as follows:

> Sound similar to writ-tus and vaguely like fitz-bews but somewhat buzzier (Fig. 2H); structurally resemble a creet followed by a descending writ-tu (compare Figs. 2D, 2E, and 2H); given infrequently in aggressive contexts.

Bird seen, but species ID based solely on voice.
author: Jonathon Jongsma
